  "output": "## Performance Analysis — jobsquare\n\nThis is a Python async job-scraping pipeline (fetch → filter → dedup → notify), not a web app — there's no React/ORM here, so I've mapped your categories to the closest real equivalents in this codebase. With 132 configured sources (`sources.yaml`) each pulling up to 10-40 pages of 10-20 roles, a single run can push **10k-50k `Job` objects** through `filter_jobs()` and `Store.diff()`, which is where the two hot-path issues below actually bite.\n\n### 1. Redundant computation: regex recompiled per-job in `filters.py` (the \"N+1\" of this codebase)\n\n`filter_jobs()` calls `match(job, ...)` once per job, and `match()` calls `_compile()` on every call:\n\n```python\n# filters.py:15-27\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    ...\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every job!\n    if include:\n        if not any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(include)):  # recompiled every job!\n```\n\nFor N jobs and M keywords, that's O(N×M) `re.compile()` calls instead of O(M). At 20k jobs × 10 keywords, that's 200k needless compiles per run.\n\n**Fix** — compile once in `filter_jobs`, pass compiled patterns down:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations:\n        loc = job.location.lower()\n        if not any(l in loc for l in locations):\n            return False\n    ...\n```\n\n### 2. N+1 SQLite queries in `Store.diff()`\n\n```python\n# store.py:60-72\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nOne `SELECT` per job — N round-trips through SQLite's statement-prep/execute overhead instead of a single bulk read. `key` is the primary key, so each lookup is a fast B-tree hit, but at 20k jobs the per-call Python↔SQLite overhead (~tens of µs each) adds real wall-clock time, and this pattern will get worse if the store ever moves off local SQLite.\n\n**Fix** — load all existing `(key, content_hash)` pairs once into a dict, diff in Python, then write with a single batch:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = dict(self.conn.execute(\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs\"))\n    new, changed, unchanged_keys = [], [], []\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        if h is None:\n            new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n        elif h != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job); self._update(cur, job, now)\n        else:\n            unchanged_keys.append(job.key)\n    if unchanged_keys:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\",\n                         [(now, k) for k in unchanged_keys])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nThis turns N SELECT statements into 1, and batches the \"touch\" updates via `executemany`.\n\n### 3. Redundant hashing: `Job.content_hash`/`Job.key` recomputed multiple times per job\n\nBoth are plain `@property` (no caching — `slots=True` rules out `functools.cached_property` as-is), and each is computed 2-3× per job in the write path: once in `Store.diff()` (`job.key`, `job.content_hash` comparison), again inside `to_row()` (`self.key`, `self.content_hash`) called by `_insert`/`_update`. `content_hash` does a SHA-256 over concatenated fields — cheap per call, but multiplied by tens of thousands of jobs it's wasted CPU for no reason.\n\n**Fix** — compute once per job and thread the value through, e.g. add explicit slots for cached values:\n\n```python\n@dataclass(slots=True)\nclass Job:\n    ...\n    _key: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n    _hash: str | None = field(default=None, repr=False, compare=False)\n\n    @property\n    def key(self) -> str:\n        if self._key is None:\n            self._key = f\"{self.source}:{self.company}:{self.external_id}\"\n        return self._key\n\n    @property\n    def content_hash(self) -> str:\n        if self._hash is None:\n            blob = \"|\".join((self.title, self.location, self.url, self.department))\n            self._hash = hashlib.sha256(blob.encode()).hexdigest()[:16]\n        return self._hash\n```\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity: no conditional HTTP requests / no persistent connection pool across runs\n\nEvery scheduled run (the repo has a 12h scheduler per `6ae8083`) opens a fresh `httpx.AsyncClient` in `fetch_all()` and re-downloads the *entire* board for all 132 sources from scratch — full JSON for boards with thousands of roles (Amazon, Microsoft, Google, Apple), even though most haven't changed since the last run. None of the fetchers send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, and ATS APIs that support ETags (Greenhouse, Lever, SmartRecruiters do) go unused.\n\n**Suggestion**: for the `_simple()` fetchers at least, persist and send `ETag`/`Last-Modified` per source (e.g. in the `meta` table via `store.set_meta`), and skip re-parsing on a `304`. This won't help bespoke sources (Google/Apple/Meta scraping) but would cut bandwidth/latency meaningfully for the ATS-JSON sources, which are the majority of the 132.\n\n### 5. Sequential pagination inflates latency (minor)\n\nEvery paginated fetcher (`fetch_apple`, `fetch_amazon`, `fetch_microsoft`, `fetch_google`, `fetch_workday`, etc.) awaits pages **one at a time** in a `for` loop, even though `fetch_all` already caps *cross-source* concurrency at 8 via `asyncio.Semaphore`. A single large board (e.g. Amazon at `max_pages=40`) pays 40 sequential round-trips serially. Since the stopping condition depends on seeing an empty/duplicate page, true parallelization is unsafe without extra care — but you could speculatively fetch 2-3 pages ahead and back off once a short page is seen, trading a little wasted bandwidth for wall-clock time on the biggest boards.\n\n### Non-issues (checked, no bugs found)\n\n- **Memory leaks**: none found. This is a batch CLI, not a long-lived process; `Store`/`httpx.AsyncClient` are all opened via context managers (`pipeline.py:42`, `agent.py:_store`) and closed properly, including on exceptions.\n- **`notify.py`**: dispatch is batched per-notifier (one Slack/webhook/SMS call for the whole run, not per-job) — no N+1 there.\n- **No React/frontend code exists** in this repo, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply.\n\n**Priority order**: fix #1 and #2 first — they're the only two that scale with job count and are cheap, safe, drop-in changes. #3 is a nice-to-have. #4/#5 are bigger structural changes worth doing only if run frequency/cost becomes a real problem.\n",
